Learning 4 Programming languages at the same time: C++ ,C , Python and Javascript

uninstall first: https://github.com/jupyterlab/jupyterlab-desktop/blob/master/user-guide.md#uninstalling-jupyterlab-desktop uninstall in windows with uninstaller. then delete %AppData%\jupyter and %AppData%jupyterlab-desktop and also %ProgramData%\jupyter.

make sure that you select

Does this really make sense. C++, C are compiled languages, Python and Javascript are interpreted languages. But they have quite a few similar notations and it is quite easy to learn them in one run.

Setup of C/C++ in Jupyterlab

Download Jupyterlab for your platform from: https://github.com/jupyterlab/jupyterlab-desktop Confirmed working on: Version 4.0.12 Currently Version 4.1 does not work with root 6.30.04 as it uses python 3.12 and root uses python 3.8.

install root from root cern. https://root.cern/install/all_releases/ confirmed working on:Release 6.30.04 - 2024-01-31

In the following I assume that root installs into: C:\root_v6.30.04 you might have to replace it accordingly. Add the folder C:\root_v6.30.04\bin to your system path variable: https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/office/developer/sharepoint-2010/ee537574(v=office.14)

now edit C:\root_v6.30.04\etc\notebook\kernels\root\kernel.json replace the version according to your installation!

{
"language": "python",
"display_name": "ROOT python",
"argv": [
    "C:\\Users\\admin\\AppData\\Roaming\\jupyterlab-desktop\\jlab_server\\python.exe",
    "-m",
    "ipykernel_launcher",
    "-f",
    "{connection_file}"
    ],
    "env": {
        "PYTHONPATH": "c:\\root_v6.30.04\\bin"
    }
}

open in jupyterlab the folder pane and select the + button and open a terminal. There type:

jupyter kernelspec install C:\root_v6.30.04\etc\notebook\kernels\root\
pip install metakernel

If you want to use jupyter in the browser then do (this step is optional):

pip install notebook
root --notebook

try commands from https://root.cern.ch/notebooks/HowTos/HowTo_ROOT-Notebooks.html but I set default to c++, so you need to use %%python when you do python code.

in order to execute code press shift+enter

Now with the new ROOT Python kernel you should first do

import ROOT

Then you can get cpp interpreter inside the notebook with:

cxx
cout <<"hello"

The main function in c++ or c is not needed but we will show them from time to time.

In[2]:
import ROOT

In[5]:

h.Draw()
In[6]:
c.Draw()

c++ and python work together
